WEBVTT

00:18.340 --> 00:23.280
CHAPTER XVII Doctor Seward's diary continued.

00:24.280 --> 00:30.000
When we arrived at the Berkeley Hotel, Van Helsing found a telegram waiting for him.

00:30.680 --> 00:39.680
I'm coming up by train. Jonathan at Whitby. Important news. Mina Harker. The Professor was delighted.

00:40.700 --> 00:48.000
Ah, that wonderful Madame Mina, he said. Pearl among women. She arrive, but I cannot stay.

00:48.000 --> 00:52.680
She must go to your house, friend John. You must meet her at the station.

00:53.500 --> 00:56.300
Telegraph her en route, so that she may be prepared.

00:57.280 --> 01:00.020
When the wire was dispatched, he had a cup of tea.

01:00.960 --> 01:10.900
Over it, he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs Harker's diary at Whitby.

01:10.900 --> 01:22.060
Take these, he said, and study them well. When I have returned, you will be master of all the facts, and we can then better enter on our inquisition.

01:22.700 --> 01:26.780
Keep them safe, for there is in them much of treasure.

01:27.720 --> 01:32.880
You will need all your faith, even you who have had such an experience as that of today.

01:33.520 --> 01:39.540
What is here told? He laid his hand heavily and gravely on the packet of papers as he spoke.

01:40.180 --> 01:48.060
May be the beginning of the end to you and me and many another, or it may sound the knell of the undead who walk the earth.

01:48.760 --> 01:58.180
Read all, I pray you, with the open mind, and if you can add in any way to the story here told, do so, for it is all important.

01:58.520 --> 02:02.140
You have kept a diary of all these so strange things, is it not so?

02:02.140 --> 02:06.460
Yes, then we shall go through all these together when we meet.

02:07.120 --> 02:11.520
He then made ready for his departure, and shortly drove off to Liverpool Street.

02:12.420 --> 02:17.840
I took my way to Paddington, where I arrived about fifteen minutes before the train came in.

02:18.520 --> 02:27.180
The crowd melted away after the bustling fashion common to arrival platforms, and I was beginning to feel uneasy lest I might miss my guest,

02:27.180 --> 02:32.840
when a sweet-faced dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and after a quick glance said,

02:33.400 --> 02:35.020
Doctor Seward, is it not?

02:35.440 --> 02:40.620
And you are Mrs Harker, I answered at once, whereupon she held out her hand.

02:41.260 --> 02:48.940
I knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy, but she stopped suddenly, and a quick blush overspread her face.

02:50.040 --> 02:56.440
The blush that rose to my own cheeks somehow set us both at ease, for it was a tacit answer to her own.

02:56.440 --> 03:02.960
I got her luggage, which included a typewriter, and we took the underground to Fenchurch Street,

03:03.460 --> 03:10.420
after I had sent a wire to my housekeeper to have a sitting-room and a bedroom prepared at once for Mrs Harker.

03:11.280 --> 03:15.900
In due time we arrived. She knew, of course, that the place was a lunatic asylum,

03:16.320 --> 03:20.060
but I could see that she was unable to repress her shudder when we entered.

03:20.060 --> 03:26.520
She told me that, if she might, she would come presently to my study, and she had much to say.

03:26.980 --> 03:32.360
So, here I am, finishing my entry in my phonograph diary, whilst I await her.

03:33.100 --> 03:39.700
As yet, I have not had the chance of looking at the papers which Van Helsing left with me, though they lie open before me.

03:39.940 --> 03:44.600
I must get her interested in something, so that I may have an opportunity of reading them.

03:44.600 --> 03:49.820
She does not know how precious time is, or what a task we have in hand.

03:50.500 --> 03:54.120
I must be careful not to frighten her. Here she is.

03:54.920 --> 03:57.940
Mina Harker's Journal. 29th September.

03:58.800 --> 04:02.760
After I had tidied myself, I went down to Dr Seward's study.

04:03.760 --> 04:07.840
At the door I paused a moment, for I thought I heard him talking with someone.

04:07.840 --> 04:16.500
As, however, he had pressed me to be quick, I knocked at the door, and, on his calling out, come in, I entered.

04:16.960 --> 04:20.040
To my intense surprise, there was no one with him.

04:20.380 --> 04:27.420
He was quite alone, and on the table opposite him was what I knew at once from the description to be a phonograph.

04:28.140 --> 04:30.880
I had never seen one, and was much interested.

04:30.880 --> 04:33.960
I hope I did not keep you waiting, I said.

04:34.440 --> 04:39.320
But I stayed at the door, as I heard you talking, and thought there was someone with you.

04:39.700 --> 04:43.040
Oh, he replied with a smile. I was only entering my diary.

04:43.700 --> 04:46.240
Your diary? I asked him in surprise.

04:47.080 --> 04:49.740
Yes, he answered. I keep it in this.

04:50.400 --> 04:53.240
As he spoke, he laid his hand on the phonograph.

04:53.900 --> 04:59.540
I felt quite excited over it, and blurted out, Why, this beats even shorthand.

04:59.540 --> 05:01.460
May I hear it say something?

05:02.340 --> 05:06.820
Certainly, he replied with alacrity, and stood up to put it in train for speaking.

05:07.720 --> 05:11.380
Then he paused, and a troubled look overspread his face.

05:11.900 --> 05:21.720
The fact is, he began awkwardly, I only keep my diary in it, and as it is entirely, almost entirely, about my cases, it may be awkward.

05:23.040 --> 05:27.800
That is, I mean, he stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment.

05:28.460 --> 05:35.860
You helped to attend dear Lucy at the end. Let me hear how she died. For all that I know of her, I shall be very grateful.

05:36.500 --> 05:38.940
She was very, very dear to me.

05:39.760 --> 05:47.360
To my surprise, he answered, with a horostruck look in his face, Tell you of her death, not for the wide world.

05:47.940 --> 05:52.280
Why not? I asked, for some grave terrible feeling was coming over me.

05:52.800 --> 05:57.240
Again he paused, and I could see that he was trying to invent an excuse.

05:57.240 --> 06:05.520
At length, he stammered out, You see, I do not know how to pick out any particular part of the diary.

06:06.000 --> 06:09.220
Even while he was speaking, an idea dawned upon him.

06:09.380 --> 06:16.200
And, he said, with an unconscious simplicity, in a quite different voice, and with the naivety of a child,

06:16.820 --> 06:20.420
That's quite true. Upon my honour. Honest Indian.

06:20.940 --> 06:23.680
I could not but smile, at which he grimaced.

06:23.680 --> 06:26.500
I gave myself away that time, he said.

06:27.040 --> 06:30.760
But do you know that although I have kept the diary for months past,

06:31.240 --> 06:36.620
It never once struck me how I was going to find any particular part of it, in case I wanted to look it up.

06:37.200 --> 06:41.820
By this time, my mind was made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy

06:41.820 --> 06:46.360
Might have something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible being.

06:46.360 --> 06:53.020
And I said, boldly, Then, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you, on my typewriter.

06:53.900 --> 07:02.980
He grew to a positively deftly pallor, as he said, No, no, no, for all the world, I wouldn't let you know that terrible story.

07:03.660 --> 07:06.440
Then it was terrible. My intuition was right.

07:07.040 --> 07:14.140
For a moment I thought, and as my eyes ranged the room, unconsciously looking for something, or some opportunity to aid me,

07:14.140 --> 07:17.440
They lit on the great batch of typewriting on the table.

07:17.920 --> 07:22.900
His eyes caught the look in mine, and without his thinking followed their direction.

07:23.680 --> 07:26.420
As he saw the parcel, he realized my meaning.

07:27.020 --> 07:28.860
You do not know me, I said.

07:29.580 --> 07:36.040
When you have read these papers, my own diary, and my husband's also, which I have typed, you will know me better.

07:36.660 --> 07:41.020
I have not faltered in giving every thought of my own heart in this cause.

07:41.020 --> 07:47.060
But, of course, you do not know me yet, and I must not expect you to trust me so far.

07:47.840 --> 07:52.400
He is certainly a man of noble nature. Poor dear Lucy was right about him.

07:52.800 --> 08:02.680
He stood up and opened a large drawer, in which were arranged, in order, a number of hollow cylinders of metal, covered with dark wax, and said,

08:02.680 --> 08:12.180
You are quite right. I did not trust you, because I did not know you, but I know you now, and let me say that I should have known you long ago.

08:12.860 --> 08:16.360
I know that Lucy told you of me. She told me of you, too.

08:17.040 --> 08:19.140
May I make the only atonement in my power?

08:20.000 --> 08:26.680
Take the cylinders, and hear them. The first half-dozen of them are personal to me, and they will not horrify you.

08:27.480 --> 08:29.180
Then you will know me better.

08:29.780 --> 08:38.700
Dinner will by then be ready. In the meantime, I shall read over some of these documents, and shall be better able to understand certain things.

08:39.960 --> 08:44.460
He carried the phonograph himself up to my sitting-room, and adjusted it for me.

08:45.040 --> 08:54.000
Now I shall learn something pleasant, I am sure, for it will tell me the other side of a true love episode of which I know one side already.

08:55.160 --> 08:58.000
Dr. Seward's Diary, 29th September

08:58.680 --> 09:06.720
I was so absorbed in that wonderful diary of Jonathan Harker, and that of his wife, that I let the time run on without thinking.

09:07.860 --> 09:17.660
Mrs. Harker was not down when the maid came to announce dinner, so I said, She is possibly tired, let dinner wait an hour, and I went on with my work.

09:18.620 --> 09:22.000
I had just finished Mrs. Harker's diary, when she came in.

09:22.000 --> 09:30.680
She looked sweetly pretty, but very sad, and her eyes were flushed with crying. This somehow moved me much.

09:31.540 --> 09:42.600
Of late I have had cause for tears, God knows, but the relief of them was denied me, and now the sight of those sweet eyes, brightened by recent tears, went straight to my heart.

09:43.440 --> 09:48.980
So, I said as gently as I could, I greatly fear I have distressed you.

09:48.980 --> 09:58.940
Oh no, not distressed me, she replied, but I have been more touched than I can say by your grief. That is a wonderful machine, but it is cruelly true.

09:59.640 --> 10:10.240
It told me, in its very tones, the anguish of your heart. It was like a soul crying out to Almighty God. No one must hear them spoken ever again.

10:10.980 --> 10:20.160
See, I have tried to be useful. I have copied out the words on my typewriter, and none of her need now hear your heartbeat as I did.

10:21.060 --> 10:25.220
No one need ever know, shall ever know, I said in a low voice.

10:26.740 --> 10:32.220
She laid her hand on mine, and said, very gravely, Ah, but they must.

10:33.420 --> 10:36.180
Must? But why? I asked.

10:37.120 --> 10:43.240
Because it is a part of the terrible story, a part of poor Lucy's death, and all that led to it.

10:43.740 --> 10:52.940
Because, in the struggle which we have before us, to rid the earth of this terrible monster, we must have all the knowledge, and all the help, which we can get.

10:53.540 --> 11:03.600
I think that the cylinders which you gave me contained more than you intended me to know, but I can see that there are, in your record, many lights to this dark mystery.

11:04.320 --> 11:18.800
You will let me help, will you not? I know all up to a certain point, and I see already that your diary only took me to the 7th of September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being wrought out.

11:18.800 --> 11:24.540
Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.

11:24.940 --> 11:29.880
He has gone to Whitby to get more information, and he will be here tomorrow to help us.

11:30.620 --> 11:39.500
We need to have no secrets amongst us. Working together, and with absolute trust, we can surely be stronger than if some of us were in the dark.

11:40.000 --> 11:48.820
She looked at me so appealingly, and at the same time manifested such courage and resolution in her bearing, that I gave in at once to her wishes.

11:49.820 --> 11:55.760
You shall, I said, do as you like in the matter. God forgive me if I do wrong.

11:56.280 --> 12:06.860
There are terrible things yet to learn of, but if you have so far travelled on the road to poor Lucy's death, you will not be content, I know, to remain in the dark.

12:06.860 --> 12:12.100
Nay, the end, the very end, may give you a gleam of peace.

12:12.780 --> 12:19.980
Come, there is dinner. We must keep one another strong for what is before us. We have a cruel and dreadful task.

12:20.620 --> 12:31.060
When you have eaten, you shall learn the rest, and I shall answer any questions you ask, if there be anything which you do not understand, though it was apparent to us who were present.

12:31.060 --> 12:34.500
Mina Harker's Journal, 29th September

12:35.240 --> 12:38.560
After dinner, I came with Dr Seward to his study.

12:39.780 --> 12:51.320
He brought back the phonograph from my room, and I took a chair and arranged the phonograph so that I could touch it without getting up, and showed me how to stop it in case I should want to pause.

12:51.940 --> 12:59.960
Then he very thoughtfully took a chair with his back to me, so that I might be as free as possible, and began to read.

12:59.960 --> 13:03.600
I put the forked metal to my ears and listened.

13:04.720 --> 13:11.480
When the terrible story of Lucy's death and all that followed was done, I lay back in my chair, powerless.

13:13.040 --> 13:15.920
Fortunately, I am not of a fainting disposition.

13:16.620 --> 13:30.600
When Dr Seward saw me, he jumped up with a horrified exclamation, and, hurriedly taking a case bottle from the cupboard, gave me some brandy, which, in a few minutes, somewhat restored me.

13:30.900 --> 13:44.000
My brain was all in a whirl, and only that there came, through all the multitude of horrors, the holy ray of light that my dear Lucy was at last at peace, I do not think that I could have borne it without making a scene.

13:44.000 --> 13:53.480
It is all so wild and mysterious, and strange, that if I had not known Jonathan's experience in Transylvania, I could not have believed.

13:54.360 --> 14:00.960
As it was, I didn't know what to believe, and so got out of my difficulty by attending to something else.

14:01.880 --> 14:05.480
I took the cover off my typewriter, and said to Dr Seward,

14:05.480 --> 14:10.900
Let me write this all out now. We must be ready for Dr Van Helsing when he comes.

14:11.560 --> 14:16.340
I have sent a telegram to Jonathan to come on here when he arrives in London from Whitby.

14:17.180 --> 14:27.160
In this matter, dates are everything, and I think that if we get all of our material ready, and to have every item put in chronological order, we shall have done much.

14:27.160 --> 14:34.480
You tell me that Lord Goodalming and Mr Morris are coming too. Let us be able to tell them when they come.

14:35.660 --> 14:42.720
He accordingly set the phonograph at a slow pace, and I began to type-write from the beginning of the seventeenth cylinder.

14:43.760 --> 14:50.040
I used manifold, and so took three copies of the diary, just as I had done with the rest.

14:50.680 --> 14:56.060
It was late when I got through, but Dr Seward went about his work of going his round of the patients.

14:56.620 --> 15:04.600
When he had finished, he came back and sat near me, reading, so that I did not feel too lonely whilst I worked.

15:05.180 --> 15:11.220
How good and thoughtful he is! The world seems full of good men, even if there are monsters in it.

15:12.300 --> 15:20.380
Before I left him, I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the professor's perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter.

15:21.420 --> 15:30.240
So, seeing that Dr Seward keeps his newspapers, I borrowed the files of the Westminster Gazette and the Pall Mall Gazette, and took them to my room.

15:30.940 --> 15:40.420
I remember how much the Daily Graph and the Whitby Gazette, of which I had made cuttings, had helped us to understand the terrible events at Whitby when Count Dracula landed.

15:41.060 --> 15:49.500
So I shall look through the evening papers since then, and perhaps I shall get some new light. I am not sleepy, and the work will help to keep me quiet.

15:50.800 --> 15:52.760
Dr Seward's Diary

15:52.760 --> 15:54.100
30th September

15:54.660 --> 16:05.260
Mr Harker arrived at nine o'clock. He got his wife's wire just before starting. He is uncommonly clever, if one can judge from his face, and full of energy.

16:06.160 --> 16:13.540
If this journal be true, and judging by one's own wonderful experiences it must be, he is also a man of great nerve.

16:13.540 --> 16:28.200
That going down to the vault a second time was a remarkable piece of daring. After reading his account of it, I was prepared to meet a good specimen of manhood, but hardly the quiet businesslike gentleman who came here today.

16:29.240 --> 16:29.620
Later

16:29.620 --> 16:40.640
After lunch, Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and as I passed a while ago, I heard the click of the typewriter. They are hard at it.

16:40.640 --> 16:47.140
Mrs Harker says that they are knitting together, in chronological order, every scrap of evidence they have.

16:48.260 --> 17:00.740
Harker has got the letters between the consignee of the boxes at Whitby, and the carriers in London who took charge of them. He is now reading his wife's transcript of my diary. I wonder what they will make out of it.

17:01.700 --> 17:12.680
Here it is. Strange that it never struck me that the very next house might be the Count's hiding place. Goodness knows that we had enough clues from the conduct of the patient Renfield.

17:13.860 --> 17:25.580
The bundle of letters relating to the purchase of the house were with the transcript. Oh, if we had only had them earlier, we might have saved poor Lucy. Stop! That way madness lies.

17:27.320 --> 17:47.280
Harker has gone back, and is again collecting material. He says that by dinnertime they will be able to show a whole connected narrative. He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.

17:47.980 --> 17:59.620
I hardly see this yet, but when I get at the dates I suppose I shall. What a good thing that Mrs Harker put my cylinders into type. We never could have found the dates otherwise.

17:59.620 --> 18:17.220
I found Renfield sitting placidly in his room, with his hands folded, smiling benignly. At the moment he seemed as sane as anyone I ever saw. I sat down and talked with him on a lot of subjects, all of which he treated naturally.

18:17.220 --> 18:31.820
He then, of his own accord, spoke of going home, a subject he has never mentioned to my knowledge during his sojourn here. In fact he spoke quite confidently of getting his discharge at once.

18:32.540 --> 18:42.960
I believe that had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.

18:42.960 --> 18:59.540
As it is, I am darkly suspicious. All those outbreaks were in some way linked with the proximity of the Count. What then does this absolute content mean? Can it be that his instinct is satisfied as to the Vampire's ultimate triumph?

18:59.540 --> 19:14.820
Stay. He is himself Zufagus, and in his wild ravings outside the chapel door of the deserted house, he always spoke of Master. This all seems confirmation of our idea.

19:14.820 --> 19:26.820
However, after a while I came away. My friend is just a little too sane at present to make it safe to probe him too deep with questions. He might begin to think, and then...

19:27.820 --> 19:39.800
So I came away. I mistrust these quiet moods of his, so I have given the attendant a hint to look closely after him and to have a straight waistcoat ready in case of need.

19:39.800 --> 19:45.540
Jonathan Harker's Journal. 29th September. In train to London.

19:46.920 --> 19:58.540
When I received Mr. Billington's courteous message that he would give me any information in his power, I thought it best to go down to Whitby and make, on the spot, such inquiries as I wanted.

19:58.540 --> 20:08.440
It was now my object to trace that horrid cargo of the Count's to its place in London. Later we may be able to deal with it.

20:08.820 --> 20:21.260
Billington Jr., a nice lad, met me at the station and brought me to his father's house, where they had decided that I must spend the night. They are hospitable, with true Yorkshire hospitality.

20:21.260 --> 20:35.140
Give a guest everything and leave him to do as he likes. They all knew that I was busy and that my stay was short, and Mr. Billington had ready, in his office, all the papers concerning the consignment of boxes.

20:35.820 --> 20:43.080
It gave me almost a turn to see again one of the letters which I had seen at the Count's table, before I knew of his diabolical plans.

20:43.080 --> 20:56.880
Everything had been carefully thought out and done systematically and with precision. He seems to have been prepared for every obstacle which might be placed by accident in the way of his intentions being carried out.

20:57.540 --> 21:08.620
To use an Americanism, he had taken no chances, and the absolute accuracy with which his instructions were fulfilled was simply the logical result of his care.

21:08.620 --> 21:25.040
I saw the invoice and took note of it. 50 cases of Common Earth to be used for experimental purposes. Also the copy of the letter to Carter Paterson, and their reply. Of both these I got copies.

21:25.040 --> 21:41.240
This was all the information Mr. Billington could give me, so I went down to the port and saw the Coast Guards, the Customs Officers and the Harbour Master, who kindly put me in communication with the men who had actually received the boxes.

21:41.900 --> 21:56.640
Their tally was exact with the list, and they had nothing to add to the simple description, 50 cases of Common Earth, except that the boxes were main and mortal heavy, and that shifting them was dry work.

21:56.640 --> 22:08.640
One of them added that it was hard lines that there wasn't any gentleman such like as like yourself, Squire, to show some sort of appreciation of their efforts in a liquid form.

22:08.640 --> 22:18.480
Another put in a rider that the first then generated was such that even the time which had elapsed had not completely elated.

22:18.960 --> 22:27.540
Needless to add, I took care before leaving to lift, forever and adequately, this source of reproach.

22:28.380 --> 22:42.960
30th September. The Station Master was good enough to give me a line to his old companion, the Station Master at King's Cross, so that when I arrived there in the morning, I was able to ask him about the arrival of the boxes.

22:43.620 --> 22:51.640
He, too, put me at once in communication with the proper officials, and I saw that their tally was correct with the original invoice.

22:51.640 --> 23:05.840
The opportunities of acquiring an abnormal first had been, here, limited. A noble use of them had, however, been made, and again I was compelled to deal with the result in ex post facto manner.

23:07.220 --> 23:21.640
From thence I went to Carter Paterson's central office, where I met with the utmost courtesy. They looked up the transaction in their day book and letter book, and at once telephoned to their King's Cross office for more details.

23:21.640 --> 23:36.820
By good fortune, the men who did the teaming were waiting for work, and the official at once sent them over, sending also, by one of them, the way bill and all the papers connected with the delivery of the boxes at Carfax.

23:36.820 --> 23:40.580
Here, again, I found the tally agreeing exactly.

23:41.780 --> 23:57.200
The carrier's men were able to supplement the paucity of the written words with a few more details. These were, I shortly found, connected almost solely with the dusty nature of the job, and the consequent first engendered in the operators.

23:57.800 --> 24:08.200
On my affording an opportunity, through the medium of the currency of the realm, of the allaying at a later period this beneficial evil, one of the men remarked,

24:08.820 --> 24:21.380
That airhouse, Governor, is the rummiest I ever was in. Blimey, but it ain't been touched since a hundred years. There was just that thick in the place that you might have slept on it without hurting of your bones.

24:22.080 --> 24:37.740
And the place was that neglected that you might have smelled old Jerusalem in it. But the old chapel, that took the sight that did. Me and my mate, we thought we wouldn't never get out quick enough, or I wouldn't take less nor a quid a moment to stay there out of dark.

24:37.740 --> 24:46.080
Having been in the house, I could well believe him. But if he knew what I know, he would, I think, have raised his terms.

24:46.980 --> 24:57.000
Of one thing I am now satisfied, that all those boxes which arrived at Whitby from Varna in the Demeter were safely deposited in the old chapel at Carfax.

24:57.760 --> 25:03.920
There should be fifty of them there, unless any have since been removed, as from Dr. Seward's diary, I fear.

25:04.580 --> 25:11.040
Later, Mina and I have worked all day, and we have put all the papers into order.

25:11.680 --> 25:19.560
Mina Harker's Journal. 30th September. I am so glad that I hardly know how to contain myself.

25:20.500 --> 25:29.920
It is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act detrimentally on Jonathan.

25:29.920 --> 25:35.840
I saw him leave for Whitby with as brave a face as could, but I was sick with apprehension.

25:36.720 --> 25:46.440
The effort has, however, done him good. He was never so resolute, never so strong, never so full of volcanic energy as at present.

25:46.920 --> 25:55.280
It is just as that good, dear Professor Van Helsing said. He is true grit, and he improves under strain that would kill a weaker nature.

25:55.280 --> 26:02.800
He came back full of life and hope and determination. We have got everything in order for tonight.

26:03.640 --> 26:09.720
I feel myself quite wild of excitement. I suppose one ought to pity anything so hunted as the Count.

26:10.620 --> 26:15.140
That is just it. This thing is not human, not even a beast.

26:16.040 --> 26:23.180
To read Dr. Seward's diary of poor Lucy's death and what followed is enough to dry up the springs of pity in one's heart.

26:24.340 --> 26:29.400
Later, Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris arrived earlier than we expected.

26:30.500 --> 26:35.960
Dr. Seward was out on business and had taken Jonathan with him, so I had to see them.

26:36.420 --> 26:42.920
It was, to me, a painful meeting, for it brought back all poor dear Lucy's hopes of only a few months ago.

26:43.560 --> 26:52.820
Of course, they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, had been quite blowing my trumpet, as Mr. Morris expressed it.

26:52.820 --> 26:58.360
Poor fellows, neither of them is aware that I know all about the proposals they made to Lucy.

26:59.320 --> 27:07.580
They did not quite know what to say or do, as they were ignorant of the amount of my knowledge, so they had to keep on neutral subjects.

27:08.680 --> 27:16.920
However, I thought the matter over and came to the conclusion that the best thing I could do would be to post them on affairs right up to date.

27:17.480 --> 27:26.120
I knew from Dr. Seward's diary that they had been at Lucy's death, a real death, and that I need not fear to betray any secret before the time.

27:26.660 --> 27:36.700
So I told them, as well as I could, that I had read all the papers and diaries and that my husband and I, having typewritten them, had just finished putting them into order.

27:37.220 --> 27:44.440
I gave them each a copy to read in the library. When Lord Godalming got it and turned it over, it does make a pretty good pile.

27:44.440 --> 27:50.820
He said, Did you write all this, Mrs. Harker? I nodded, and he went on.

27:51.160 --> 28:04.580
I don't quite see the drift of it, but you people are all so good and kind and have been working so earnestly and so energetically that all I can do is to accept your ideas blindfold and try to help you.

28:05.040 --> 28:11.260
I have had one lesson already in accepting facts that should make a man humble to the last hour of his life.

28:11.260 --> 28:14.300
Besides, I know you loved my Lucy.

28:15.540 --> 28:22.560
Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands. I could hear the tears in his voice.

28:23.360 --> 28:32.060
Mr. Morris, with instinctive delicacy, just laid a hand for a moment on his shoulder and then walked quietly out of the room.

28:32.060 --> 28:45.340
I suppose there is something in a woman's nature that makes a man free to break down before her and express his feelings on the tender or emotional side without feeling it derogatory to his manhood.

28:45.420 --> 28:53.000
For, when Lord Godalming found himself alone with me, he sat down on the sofa and gave way utterly and openly.

28:53.720 --> 28:56.560
I sat down beside him and took his hand.

28:57.340 --> 29:04.380
I hope he didn't think it forward of me, and that if he ever thinks of it afterwards he will never have such a thought.

29:05.160 --> 29:09.720
There I rang him. I know he never will. He is too true a gentleman.

29:10.740 --> 29:14.100
I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking.

29:14.680 --> 29:19.960
I loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you and what you were to her.

29:19.960 --> 29:23.580
She and I were like sisters, and now she is gone.

29:24.660 --> 29:28.000
Will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?

29:28.540 --> 29:33.040
I know what sorrows you have had, though I cannot measure the depth of them.

29:33.760 --> 29:40.740
If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won't you let me be of some little service for Lucy's sake?

29:41.600 --> 29:46.280
In an instant the poor dear fellow was overwhelmed with grief.

29:46.280 --> 29:53.060
It seemed to me that all that he had of late been suffering in silence found a vent at once.

29:53.660 --> 30:01.760
He grew quite hysterical, and, raising his open hands, beat his palms together in a perfect agony of grief.

30:02.140 --> 30:07.380
He stood up, and then sat down again, and the tears rained down his cheeks.

30:08.320 --> 30:12.740
I felt an infinite pity for him, and opened my arms unthinkingly.

30:12.740 --> 30:21.260
With a sob, he laid his head on my shoulder, and cried like a weary child, whilst he shook with emotion.

30:21.900 --> 30:28.680
We women have something of the mother in us that makes us rise above smaller matters when the mother spirit is invoked.

30:29.380 --> 30:37.820
I felt this big, sorrowing man's head resting on me, as though it were that of a baby that some day may lie on my bosom,

30:37.820 --> 30:41.780
and I stroked his hair as though he were my own child.

30:43.220 --> 30:46.020
I never thought at the time how strange it all was.

30:46.720 --> 30:54.520
After a little bit, his sob ceased, and he raised himself with an apology, though he made no disguise of his emotion.

30:55.380 --> 31:07.060
He told me that for days and nights past, weary days and sleepless nights, he had been unable to speak with anyone as a man must speak in his time of sorrow.

31:07.060 --> 31:17.020
There was no woman whose sympathy could be given to him, or with whom, owing to the terrible circumstances with which his sorrow was surrounded, he could speak freely.

31:17.720 --> 31:21.920
I know now how I suffered, he said, as he dried his eyes.

31:22.560 --> 31:29.840
But I do not know even yet, and none other can ever know, how much your sweet sympathy has been to me today.

31:29.840 --> 31:38.240
I shall know better in time, and believe me that though I am not ungrateful now, my gratitude will grow with my understanding.

31:39.080 --> 31:44.360
You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives, for dear Lucy's sake?

31:44.840 --> 31:48.620
For dear Lucy's sake, I said, as we clasped hands.

31:49.460 --> 31:59.260
I, and for your own sake, he added, for, if a man's esteem and gratitude are ever worth the winning, you have won mine today.

32:01.060 --> 32:07.920
If ever the future should bring to you a time when you need a man's help, believe me, you will not call in vain.

32:08.600 --> 32:17.240
God grant that no such time may ever come to you to break the sunshine of your life, but if it should ever come, promise me that you will let me know.

32:17.240 --> 32:22.900
He was so earnest, and his sorrow was so fresh, that I felt it would comfort him.

32:23.360 --> 32:29.880
So I said, I promise. As I came along the corridor, I saw Mr. Morris looking out of a window.

32:30.800 --> 32:32.660
He turned as he heard my footsteps.

32:33.340 --> 32:34.800
How is Art? he said.

32:35.420 --> 32:39.240
Then, noticing my red eyes, he went on.

32:39.400 --> 32:42.420
Ah, I see you have been comforting him.

32:43.280 --> 32:45.600
Poor old fellow, he needs it.

32:45.980 --> 32:52.100
No one but a woman can help a man when he is in trouble of the heart, and he had no one to comfort him.

32:52.820 --> 32:56.900
He bore his own trouble so bravely that my heart bled for him.

32:57.500 --> 33:03.180
I saw the manuscript in his hand, and I knew that when he read it, he would realize how much I knew.

33:03.820 --> 33:08.160
So I said to him, I wish I could comfort all who suffer from the heart.

33:08.160 --> 33:13.340
Will you let me be your friend, and will you come to me for comfort if you need it?

33:13.860 --> 33:15.700
You will know later why I speak.

33:16.560 --> 33:24.400
He saw that I was in earnest, and stooping, took my hand, and, raising it to his lips, kissed it.

33:24.940 --> 33:33.040
It seemed poor comfort to so brave an unselfish a soul, and impulsively, I bent over and kissed him.

33:33.040 --> 33:37.660
The tears rose in his eyes, and there was a momentary choking in his throat.

33:38.380 --> 33:40.240
He said, quite calmly,

33:41.100 --> 33:46.540
Little girl, you will never forget that true-hearted kindness so long as ever you live.

33:46.980 --> 33:50.280
Then he went into the study to his friend.

33:51.220 --> 33:58.400
Little girl, the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend.

34:03.040 --> 34:04.180
Chapter 17

